Earlier today the sun was blacked out by the shadow of the moon for up
to four minutes along a 108-mile swath that moved from the Indian
Ocean across Indonesia and the southern Philippine Island of
Mindanao. The eclipse was partial across a wide area of Asia and parts
of Australia. Natives danced, banged drums and participated in other
traditional activities in celebration of the phenomenon. Despite some
cloud cover, scientists were able to take pictures of the
eclipse. Eclipses occur when the moon is positioned between the earth
and the sun. The Chinese first recorded an eclipse in 2137 B.C.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d08"
TYPE="PERDOC"
